    40	
    41	billion across 2,711 gifts to 2,545 organizations since 2019 (Yield Giving 2026). Almost none of
    42	it is denominated in health, and, to my knowledge, no published estimate prices the portfolio in
    43	outcomes of any kind.
    44	This paper does so in the unit health economists use to compare a death averted against years
    45	lived in better health: the quality-adjusted life-year. The exercise is deliberately in the style
    46	of a charity evaluator’s cost-effectiveness analysis (GiveWell 2025), scaled from a program to a
    47	portfolio, with one addition the setting forces: because most of the portfolio funds interventions
    48	whose health effects have never been causally measured, the model makes its epistemics explicit.
    49	Every effect is shrunk toward zero in proportion to how well its supporting study identifies
    50	causation, the shrinkage schedule is a slider rather than a buried constant, and the headline
    51	is reported across the full range of evidence philosophies — from counting only randomized
    52	evidence to taking every published estimate at face value.
    53	The paper makes four contributions. It provides what I believe is the first outside, portfolio-level
    54	cost-effectiveness estimate of Scott’s giving, and I have found no comparable outside estimate
    55	for any other individual mega-donor — funder-run portfolio metrics exist, including GiveWell’s
    56	aggregate impact estimates (GiveWell 2025), Robin Hood’s benefit–cost framework (Robin Hood
    57	Foundation 2023), the Constellation Fund’s portfolio reporting (Constellation Fund 2026), and
    58	social-rate-of-return analysis of USAID’s Development Innovation Ventures portfolio (Center
    59	for Effective Global Action 2022); the difference here is independence from the donor, a subject
    60	who publishes no outcome data, and explicit evidence weighting: a best-guess median of 202,000
    61	QALYs from $26.39 billion nominal ($30.3B in 2026 dollars), a blended $150,067 per QALY, and a
    62	median benefit–cost ratio of 4.9 under the HHS regulatory value-per-QALY distribution (Kearsley
    63	2026). It estimates extreme geographic concentration of impact under its pricing assumptions:
    64	the 4.8% of dollars funding global health and development delivered outside the United States
    65	accounts for 69.1% of estimated health impact. It reports a new empirical regularity in the
    66	gift data itself: across 1,313 disclosed gift–filing pairs, gift size scales with recipient pre-gift
    67	revenue to the power 0.41 (R² 0.37) — Scott’s giving is far flatter across organization size than
    68	proportional. And it demonstrates a working method for auditable, AI-assisted cost-effectiveness
    69	modeling: the model was built with a frontier language model, reviewed and corrected in public
    70	through the revision history summarized in the robustness section, audited by two independent
    71	model families against primary filings, and ships with versioned parameters, machine-checked
    72	citations, and a browser implementation that reruns the full Monte Carlo under any reader’s
    73	assumptions.
    74	The unit of account deserves a caveat before any number. QALYs measure health. Most of Scott’s
    75	portfolio aims at other things — education, economic mobility, equity, civic infrastructure —
    76	whose primary benefits are not health benefits. A finding that a dollar of education philanthropy
    77	produces few QALYs is a statement about the lens, not a verdict on the gift. The estimates
    78	are a partial, health-only accounting under positive-effect priors — not a lower bound on total
    79	wellbeing: the lens omits the primary intended benefits of most of the portfolio, and the model
    80	places no probability on zero or harmful effects, a structural choice the limitations section returns
    81	to.
    82	
