    85	2 Data
    95	granular: a gift-level database listing every recipient organization, its self-reported focus areas,
    96	and — for 2,035 of 2,711 gifts ($17.46B, about two-thirds of the nominal total) — the dollar
    97	amount. Each organization’s dollars are split equally across its focus areas; the database’s
    98	53 areas map onto the model’s 14 intervention archetypes under a documented, sync-tested
    99	crosswalk.
   100	The undisclosed third is imputed rather than dropped. Because the essays give each year’s
   101	total, the undisclosed residual per period is a known dollar amount; it is distributed across that
   102	period’s undisclosed gifts in proportion to each recipient’s pre-gift IRS Form 990 total revenue
   103	(ProPublica 2026), raised to an elasticity fit on the disclosed pairs. Pre-gift means the latest
   104	filing strictly before the gift year, since a Scott gift mechanically inflates receipt-year revenue.
   105	The fit is a finding in its own right: across 1,313 disclosed gift–filing pairs, log gift size rises
   106	with log revenue with slope 0.41 (R² 0.37). A 10× larger organization receives about 2.5× more
   107	money, not 10× more. The fit is descriptive and conditional: it is estimated on disclosed gifts
   108	with a matched pre-gift filing (1,313 of 2,035 disclosed and 2,711 total gifts), treats repeated
   109	gifts to an organization as independent, and pools years; 287 of the 676 undisclosed gifts lack
   110	a usable filing and receive their period’s median weight. It is a within-sample regularity used
   111	for imputation, not a validated prediction rule. Fuzzy name-to-EIN matches were audited by
   112	a third, smaller model against the live IRS API, with corrections committed as a reviewable
   113	overlay. The imputed third moves each cause share by at most about 1.5 percentage points —
   114	under the imputation model, the disclosed two-thirds is representative.
   115	
   116	2.3 Delivery geography
   117	Each organization reports service locations. Weighting disclosed dollars by the audited share of
   118	each organization’s locations outside the United States, an estimated 19% of disclosed dollars
   119	($3.34B of $17.46B) sits with organizations reporting non-U.S. service locations — 20.4% under
   120	the raw rule that counts a bare “global” listing as fully non-U.S. — led by environment, health,
   121	and funding intermediaries. Locations are an equal-split proxy: a listed location is not an
   122	expenditure share, and no organization reports how Scott’s own gift was deployed. The model
   123	prices geography through a single channel: health-relevant dollars route to a global-health
   124	archetype in proportion to the recipient’s non-U.S. service share, because global health delivery
   125	
   126	3
   127	
   128	is the one category with a published cost-per-QALY evidence base an order of magnitude below
   129	U.S. anchors. Education and climate dollars keep their U.S.-study anchors wherever they are
   130	delivered; if geography changes their effectiveness, the model does not capture it.
   131	The coarsest geographic field is the bare label “global.” An audit of the 50 organizations with the
   132	most dollars attached to that label — 87% of its dollars; 20 of the 50 also list other locations —
   133	replaced the blanket assumption of fully-abroad delivery with fractions coded independently by
   134	two model families from each organization’s filings and program reports, then reconciled — the
   135	second coder confirmed 33 within tolerance and disputed 17; four disputes were adjudicated to
   136	documented filings arithmetic, and final fractions average the two coders everywhere else, with
   137	per-organization sources and confidence grades — 16 high, 17 medium, 17 low — committed to
   138	the repository. Many “global” organizations operate substantially in the United States: Planned
   139	Parenthood and Crisis Text Line, for example, list “global” service but are roughly 95% and
   140	93% U.S. in their most recent organization-wide reporting — later-period proxies for how earlier
   141	gifts were deployed, since neither reports gift-level allocation. The audited allocation routes
   142	4.82% of the ledger to the global health and development archetype. That routed bucket is itself
   143	mixed: its dollars sit 42% in Sub-Saharan Africa, 20% in South Asia, and 11% in Latin America,
   144	but 18% is unattributable multi-region activity and roughly 4% sits in Europe & Central Asia
   145	plus Canada — regions that are not classified by income here, so the bucket’s true high-income
   146	share is unidentified — all priced at the same low-and-middle-income anchors, a coarseness the
   147	limitations section flags.
   148	
   149	3 Model
   150	Each Monte Carlo draw allocates the giving across archetypes (a Dirichlet centered on the
   151	derived shares), assigns each archetype a cost per QALY drawn from a distribution anchored in
   152	published estimates, and multiplies the implied QALYs by two independent discounts. Causal
   153	credibility asks whether the measured effect is real. Each archetype carries the identification
   154	tier of its best supporting evidence, and the tier sets a Beta-distributed shrinkage factor toward
   155	the null: a lottery-randomized wealth shock (Cesarini et al. 2016) or the Medicaid mortality
   156	quasi-experiments — the ACA expansions (Miller et al. 2021), with cost–benefit arithmetic from
   157	the pre-ACA state expansions (Sommers 2017) whose spending component draws on the Oregon
   158	Health Insurance Experiment (Finkelstein et al. 2012) — keeps most of its effect; a child-targeted
   159	cash quasi-experiment (Aizer et al. 2016), with related designs catalogued in the parameter
   160	file, anchors the cash bucket; the community-health-center rollout design (Bailey and GoodmanBacon 2015) and similar contested quasi-experiments keep less; associational and assumption-only
   161	categories are shrunk near zero. Realization asks whether a marginal philanthropic dollar delivers
   162	the studied effect at all — transport to different populations, overhead, and funging, net of
   163	possible capacity effects: surveyed Scott recipients report stronger capacity and reach (Buteau
   164	et al. 2023), self-reports on whose basis the model permits realization above one (an author
   165	judgment, not a CEP effect estimate). It is one global triangular draw with mode 0.80 on support
   166	0.55–1.10.
   167	The two multipliers are designed to partition the doubt — transportability concerns in realization,
   168	identification concerns in credibility, cost-per-QALY priors stated conditional on the effect being
   169	real and delivered — though the separation is imperfect at the prior boundaries: several anchors
   170	
   171	4
   172	
   173	already average over mixed null-and-positive evidence before the credibility discount applies (a
   174	limitation noted below). Allocation uncertainty is a Dirichlet with concentration 60 around the
   175	derived centers — a judgment prior, implying for example a roughly 1.3–10% ninety-percent
   176	range on the global-health share — and represents subjective allocation uncertainty rather than
   177	sampling uncertainty propagated from the gift data pipeline. The tier ordering is the defensible
   178	part; the levels are judgment, proposed by a language model and reviewed by the author, and
   179	the results section reports the full consequence of disagreeing with them.
   180	Health effects arrive in different natural units — lives saved, life-years, depression-free days —
   181	and are converted to discounted QALYs at a 3% annual rate under source-specific conventions:
   182	adult mortality anchors sample roughly 26 remaining life-years at a utility draw centered near
   183	0.78, the frontier’s child-mortality benchmark uses a fixed ~65 remaining years at utility 0.87, and
   184	direct cost-per-QALY anchors keep their sources’ conventions. Every parameter’s unit and dollar
   185	vintage is machine-validated at load. The global-health frontier benchmark is handicapped within
   190	portfolio archetypes receive their own.
