   196	At the best-guess defaults (100,000 draws), the portfolio produces a median of 201,923 QALYs,
   197	with a 90% interval of 94,000 to 419,000 and a mean of 222,060. The interval is a probabilisticsensitivity range under the stated priors, not a confidence interval; Monte Carlo error on the
   198	median is a few hundred QALYs. The blended cost-effectiveness — dollars given over QALYs
   199	produced, at the median — is $150,067 per QALY. Monetized under the value-per-QALY
   200	distribution HHS recommends for regulatory analysis (central $726,000 at 3%; Kearsley (2026),
   201	Table 3), the median draw-level benefit–cost ratio is 4.9 (90% interval 2.1–11.0, reflecting both
   202	health-output and valuation uncertainty). Figure 1 shows the full distribution.
   203	
   204	4.1 Where it comes from
   205	Table 1 decomposes the mean estimate by cause. The result is the paper’s central contrast: the
   206	global health and development slice — 4.8% of dollars — contributes 69.1% of estimated QALYs,
   207	at a modeled cost of about $9,477 per QALY against $75,673–$305,164 for the causes with
   208	quasi-experimental or better U.S. evidence. The 1,278-fold spread in modeled cost-effectiveness
   209	within a single donor’s portfolio, under stipulated priors, is partly the lens speaking — its low
   210	end is dominated by assumption-tier buckets whose near-zero credibility is an input, and whose
   211	main benefits QALYs do not count — but the spread among evidenced health buckets alone
   212	exceeds an order of magnitude, restating in one column an empirical regularity long emphasized
