   568	4.2 Against the global-health frontier
   569	Handicapped within the same framework — sharing each draw’s realization multiplier, with
   570	RCT-grade credibility — the GiveWell-derived frontier benchmark delivers roughly 521× more
   571	health per marginal dollar than the blended portfolio; the same sum directed entirely to the
   572	frontier would imply on the order of 105.5 million QALYs. That figure is arithmetic, not a forecast,
   573	and not an attainable counterfactual: frontier-priced opportunities are scarce — GiveWell’s
   574	directed funding runs to hundreds of millions of dollars per year, not tens of billions (GiveWell
   575	2025) — and funding beyond identified room drives toward cash-transfer cost-effectiveness,
   576	whose GiveWell estimate rose 3–4× in a 2024 re-evaluation (GiveWell 2024). Converting the full
   577	portfolio at cash-transfer cost-effectiveness under this model’s own conventions leaves a multiple
   578	in the tens — roughly 20–40×, model arithmetic rather than a GiveWell figure. The defensible
   579	statement is directional: the frontier multiple is several hundred at today’s margin and remains
   580	large at any scale the cited benchmarks speak to.
