   562	4.2 Against the global-health frontier
   563	Handicapped with the same realization and credibility discounts, the GiveWell-derived frontier
   564	benchmark delivers roughly 521× more health per marginal dollar than the blended portfolio;
   565	the same sum directed entirely to the frontier would imply on the order of 105.5 million QALYs.
   566	That figure is arithmetic, not a forecast, and not an attainable counterfactual: frontier-priced
   567	opportunities are scarce — GiveWell’s directed funding runs to hundreds of millions of dollars per
   568	year, not tens of billions (GiveWell 2026) — and funding beyond identified room drives toward
   569	cash-transfer cost-effectiveness, whose GiveWell estimate rose 3–4× in a 2024 re-evaluation
   570	(GiveWell 2024). Converting the full portfolio at cash-transfer cost-effectiveness under this
   571	model’s own conventions leaves a multiple in the tens — roughly 20–40×, model arithmetic
   572	rather than a GiveWell figure. The defensible statement is directional: the frontier multiple is
   573	several hundred at today’s margin and remains large under any diminishing-returns account
   574	consistent with these benchmarks.
