paper/review/round1/red-team.md:35:   **LOCATION:** §4.2: “roughly 521×”; “105.5 million QALYs”; “same realization and credibility discounts”; “a floor plausibly under 20–40×”; “remains large under any plausible account of diminishing returns.”  
paper/review/round1/red-team.md:36:   **Problem:** The 521 and 105.5M values reproduce the code, but the interpretation does not. The $175–$241 conversion is model arithmetic—$4,000–$5,500 per life, inflated by an assumed 2023 price level and divided by 25.1 stipulated discounted QALYs—not a published GiveWell QALY estimate. GiveWell describes these figures as retrospective 2022–2024 weighted averages, warns that marginal opportunities differ, and explicitly analyzes funding opportunities rather than whole organizations ([GiveWell](https://www.givewell.org/impact-estimates)). The model does not apply the “same” credibility discount: the frontier receives an RCT-grade mean of 0.85 while portfolio archetypes receive different tier means. Multiplying a historical marginal price by $30.3B creates a knowingly unattainable 105.5M figure. The cited cash-transfer post reports a mixed consumption-and-health benchmark and does not state a 20–40× QALY floor; deriving such a range from its mortality example requires additional contestable arithmetic ([GiveWell cash review](https://blog.givewell.org/2024/11/12/re-evaluating-the-impact-of-unconditional-cash-transfers/)). “Any plausible account” is untested. “Hundreds of millions” is supportable—GiveWell says it directs several hundred million dollars per year—but it underscores that tens of billions is outside the evidence.  
paper/review/round1/red-team.md:37:   **Concrete fix:** Delete the full-portfolio 105.5M counterfactual. Report only a marginal per-dollar benchmark and finite opportunity tiers with explicit capacity. Say “the same discounting framework,” not “the same discounts.” Show the full derivation and uncertainty for any cash/QALY backstop, and remove universal language about diminishing returns.
paper/review/round2/methodology.md:11:| 5 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The false common-convention claim has been replaced by an accurate source-specific account for the default run (lines 177–187). Declining to overwrite source conventions is defensible, but the repository still exposes a general discount-rate setting that rescales only mortality conversions, VQALY, and the frontier while leaving direct cost-per-QALY anchors fixed; that control must be labeled as a partial conversion sensitivity rather than a common discount-rate scenario. |
paper/review/round2/methodology.md:12:| 6 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The methods now accurately state a shared realization draw and separate RCT-grade frontier credibility (lines 182–187), and the GiveWell-to-QALY conversion is identified as the model's. Yet the results still say “the same realization and credibility discounts” (lines 562–565), contrary to `src/msqaly/model.py`, which independently draws frontier credibility; raw/realization-only variants also remain absent. |
paper/review/round2/redteam.md:12:| 6 | PARTIALLY RESOLVED | The 105.5M extrapolation is now explicitly “arithmetic, not a forecast” and unattainable, making the decision to retain it defensible as an illustration; however, §4.2 still falsely says the frontier receives the “same realization and credibility discounts,” and the untested “any diminishing-returns account” claim remains. |
paper/review/round1/citations.md:24:   **LOCATION:** Model, p. 3, “Health effects ... are converted to discounted QALYs under a common set of conventions (about 65 remaining life-years at baseline utility 0.87, 3% annual discounting).”  
paper/review/round1/citations.md:25:   **Problem:** The values are uncited in the manuscript and are not a common conversion across the model. `data/parameters.yaml` uses roughly 26 remaining years and a 0.60/0.78/0.92 utility distribution for adult premature deaths, while 65 years and 0.87 are fixed child-death assumptions used for the global-health frontier; a third pair calibrates HHS VQALY discount-rate rescaling. The sentence therefore both overgeneralizes and conceals which conversion drives which result. GiveWell reports cost per life saved, not the 65-year or 0.87 inputs.  
paper/review/round1/citations.md:35:   **Problem:** The [ASPE landing page and 2026 PDF](https://aspe.hhs.gov/reports/standard-ria-values) identify Aaron Kearsley as author and the title as *HHS Standard Values for Regulatory Analysis, 2026*, not *Standard Values for Regulatory Impact Analysis*. The source does support the valuation input: Table 3 gives a 3%-discount VQALY range of $339,000/$726,000/$1,105,000 for 2026 impacts in constant 2025 dollars. It does not itself report the manuscript's 4.9 benefit-cost ratio, and “the U.S. government's value” is broader than the source's status as HHS default recommendations for HHS regulatory impact analyses.  
paper/review/round1/citations.md:36:   **Concrete fix:** Correct the author/title and cite Table 3. Say “using HHS's 2026 central regulatory-analysis VQALY at a 3% discount rate” (and disclose the manuscript's CPI conversion); label 4.9 and its interval as model outputs, not ASPE results.
