paper/review/sol/methodology.log:3503:+   **Problem:** The code does literally apply each of the two explicit multipliers once: \(Q_{ij}=D S_{ij}R_i C_{ij}/K_{ij}\). That establishes absence of a duplicated line of code, not the stronger claim that “each doubt enters exactly one layer.” Several cost-per-QALY priors already mix concerns assigned elsewhere. The cash prior spans adult RCT null results and positive child quasi-experiments and is then assigned a `strong_quasi` credibility multiplier; the education range is anchored to a contested literature including null findings and is then discounted again as `moderate_quasi`; and the global-health prior blends program types and GiveWell-style modeled effectiveness before receiving both credibility and realization multipliers. Conversely, the model omits harmful effects and does not propagate uncertainty about the tier means. Calling realization a “discount” is also imprecise because it can reach 1.10. The intended partition is sensible, but it is not presently demonstrated parameter by parameter and may both double-count and omit uncertainty.  
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:3504:+   **Concrete fix:** Add an uncertainty ledger for every archetype stating (i) the conditional estimand represented by its cost prior, (ii) which internal-validity concerns are excluded because credibility handles them, (iii) which transport, implementation, overhead, and funging concerns are excluded because realization handles them, and (iv) any remaining model uncertainty. Rebuild priors that already average over null-versus-positive evidence as explicitly conditional priors, or remove the overlapping credibility discount. Until that audit is complete, replace “each doubt enters exactly one layer” with “the model is intended to separate these doubts,” and report one-factor-off sensitivity runs.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:3523:+   **Problem:** The statement that outcomes are converted under a common convention of about 65 remaining years, utility 0.87, and 3% discounting is false. The 65/0.87 convention is used only for the frontier child calculation, yielding 25.12 discounted QALYs. The mortality-based health-coverage archetype instead samples 26 remaining years and utility 0.60–0.92 (mode 0.78), producing median 13.82 QALYs per death averted. Community health centers divide cost per life-year by that same adult utility draw but do not use 65 years. Direct cost-per-QALY archetypes retain their source/judgmental conventions and are not re-expressed under a common life expectancy, utility, or discount rate. Moreover, changing the discount-rate setting affects mortality conversion, VQALY, and the frontier, but leaves direct cost-per-QALY and cost-per-life-year archetypes unchanged. This is not a common-convention model outside the 3% default.  
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:3524:+   **Concrete fix:** Replace the common-convention claim with a table giving the conversion rule for every archetype and source. Either harmonize all convertible anchors to a declared 3% convention and define how direct QALY estimates respond to alternative rates, or state that the paper reports a fixed 3% analysis with source-specific QALY conventions and restrict/remove the global discount slider. Explain and justify reusing the adult mortality utility draw for the community-health-center conversion.
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:3528:+   **Problem:** “Handicapped with the same realization and credibility discounts” is not an exact description. The frontier uses the identical realization draw, which cancels algebraically from the paired frontier/portfolio multiple, but it receives a newly and independently drawn randomized-tier credibility weight. The portfolio receives a different credibility draw for every archetype at tier-specific means. Thus the comparison uses the same realization shock and the same adjustment architecture, not the same credibility discount. There is also a possible overlap requiring defense: the frontier cost prior is derived from GiveWell modeled cost per life saved, after which the model applies another generic realization factor and an RCT-grade credibility shrinkage. If the source estimates already incorporate implementation performance or evidence adjustments, this is double handicapping. The diminishing-returns caveat is strong, but it does not resolve this measurement issue.  
paper/review/sol/methodology.log:3567:+   **Problem:** The code does literally apply each of the two explicit multipliers once: \(Q_{ij}=D S_{ij}R_i C_{ij}/K_{ij}\). That establishes absence of a duplicated line of code, not the stronger claim that “each doubt enters exactly one layer.” Several cost-per-QALY priors already mix concerns assigned elsewhere. The cash prior spans adult RCT null results and positive child quasi-experiments and is then assigned a `strong_quasi` credibility multiplier; the education range is anchored to a contested literature including null findings and is then discounted again as `moderate_quasi`; and the global-health prior blends program types and GiveWell-style modeled effectiveness before receiving both credibility and realization multipliers. Conversely, the model omits harmful effects and does not propagate uncertainty about the tier means. Calling realization a “discount” is also imprecise because it can reach 1.10. The intended partition is sensible, but it is not presently demonstrated parameter by parameter and may both double-count and omit uncertainty.  
